                           @{u}Subsection: Glossary@{uu}


In the documentation for PowerCache, I have used quite a few words that may
not  mean  anything  to  inexperienced  users.   I  guess I'd better expain
(briefly) what these buzzwords mean.  Please select anything from the index
below:

	@{" Commodity " LINK Commodity}  What is a commodity?
	@{" Locale    " LINK Locale}  What is locale?
	@{" ReqLib    " LINK ReqLib}  What is Reqtools.library?
	@{" IconX     " LINK IconX}  What is IconX?
	@{" Installer " LINK Installer}  What is The Installer?
	@{" WBStartup " LINK WBStartup}  What is WBStartup?
	@{" Exchange  " LINK Exchange}  The Exchange program?
	@{" FidoNet   " LINK FidoNet}  The Fidonet network?
	@{" ARexx     " LINK ARexx}  What is ARexx?
	@{" CHelp     " LINK CHelp}  What is CHelp?
	@{" ARexxBox  " LINK ARexxBox}  What is ARexxBox?
@EndNode

@Node Commodity "What is a commodity"

A  @{b}commodity@{ub}  is a program that remains resident when run.  Commodities are
controlled  by the @{"Exchange program" LINK "Exchange"} and the commodities library system, and
often has a way to "pop up" by activating a hotkey.

Commodities is a @{b}Workbench 2.04@{ub} facility.  It is not available in operating
systems prior to this release.
@EndNode

@Node Locale "What is locale"

@{b}Locale@{ub}  is  a  means of getting programs @{i}localized@{ui}.  That is, make programs
communicate with the user in whatever language he or she prefers.

For example, if you want PowerCache to speak to you in French, all you need
to  do  is  to  select "French" as the preferred language with the "Locale"
program, located in your @{i}Prefs@{ui} drawer.  The rest should happen by itself.

Note  that  you must have a file called PowerCache.catalog in the directory
@{b}LOCALE:Catalogs/dansk/@{ub} to have PowerCache speak danish to you.  If you want
PowerCache  to  speak  French,  you  must  have  another  file, also called
@{b}PowerCache.catalog@{ub}, in the directory @{b}LOCALE:Catalogs/Français/@{ub}.

For  further information on the Locale system on the Amiga, please refer to
your @{b}Workbench 2.1@{ub} (or 3.0) documentation.

PowerCache  37.46  comes  with catalog files for localization in Danish and
English  (default  language), and since the actual CatComp source included,
other locales are bound to follow soon.
@EndNode

@Node ReqLib "What is Reqtools.library"

@{b}Reqtools.library@{ub}  is  a  set  of  functions  enabling  programs to use file
requesters,  font requesters, palette requesters, screenmode requesters and
other notification requesters.

These  are  all  very  easy  to  program, and they look much nicer than the
standard  2.04  requesters.   They  also  have  a  wide  range of bells and
whistles to make life easier for the user -- and for the programmer.

PowerCache  uses  reqtools.library for all its requesters, so naturally, it
requires  this library.  It is provided in the PowerCache distribution, and
the installation scripts automatically installs it library if it is needed.

@{u}Reqtools.library is Copyright by Nico François@{uu}.
@EndNode

@Node IconX "What is IconX"

@{b}IconX@{ub}  is  a  small program you normally keep in C:, which enables users to
execute AmigaDOS scripts directly from the Workbench (i.e.  without needing
to  start  a  seperate CLI or Shell).  All you need to do is fix up an icon
for the script, and set the @{i}default-tool@{ui} to IconX.

IconX can be acquired from most @{b}Fred Fish@{ub} disks.

PowerCache comes complete with a script for IconX, but if you have Workbench
2.1,  then  you  should really use the script provided for use with the new
@{"Installer" LINK "Installer"} program.
@EndNode

@Node Installer "What is The Installer"

@{b}The Installer@{ub} is Commodores official tool for installing software packages.
It  accepts  a  script  in  a  special  language  and  provides a neat user
interface during the installation procedure itself.

The Installer is a standard part of the new @{b}Workbench 2.1@{ub} and 3.0 operating
systems.

PowerCache  comes  complete with a script for The Installer, so if you have
2.1  or 3.0, then you should use the Installer script in stead of the @{"IconX" LINK IconX}
script.
@EndNode

@Node WBStartup "What is WBStartup"

@{b}WBStartup@{ub}  is a drawer on your system disk (or at least it should be).  Any
programs  located  in  this  drawer  will  automatically  be started by the
Workbench as soon as it is activated with @{b}LoadWB@{ub}.

You   can  put  PowerCache  into  the  WBStartup  drawer  and  have  it  run
automatically  when you start your Workbench.  Remember to add the tooltype
@{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub}  to  PowerCache's  icon,  or  Workbench  will  try  to  wait  for
PowerCache to return (which it won't :-)
@EndNode

@Node Exchange "The Exchange program"
@{b}The  Exchange@{ub}  program  is a standard part of any 2.04 system.  It provides
facilities for controlling @{"commodities" LINK Commodity}, and is itself a commodity.

PowerCache  can  be completely controlled by Exchange.  Please refer to the
relevant  system documentation on the Exchange program, for further info on
how to do this.
@EndNode

@Node FidoNet "The Fidonet network"

@{b}The  Fidonet@{ub}  is  the worlds largest, privately owned and operated network.
There  are  more  than  60,000  computer  systems running as "nodes" in the
Fidonet network, each carrying a number of "Points", or users, if you like.

Each  point  in Fidonet can mail any other point also in Fidonet, either by
"crash"  mail  where  a  message  is  sent  directly from the sender to the
receivers  node (even if it involves calling half way around the world), or
it  can  be routed through any number of other nodes.  Everyone can comment
on messages written by others, and this way spawn off other discussions and
keep the net alive.

I  could  keep  on  writing about Fidonet for several pages, and still only
scratch the surface of this huge area.

PowerCache  will  eventually  have  one  or more support BBS'es, each being
Fidonet  nodes, so that questions and suggestions can be directed at these,
as well as directly to me.

My  Fidonet  point  number  is @{b}2:230/816.8@{ub}, and if you have Fidonet access,
this  is the address you should be directing your questions and suggestions
to.
@EndNode

@Node ARexx "What is ARexx"

@{b}Rexx@{ub}  is  a  special  language,  originally developed for and used on large
mainframe  systems, for interprocess communication.  @{i}Bill Hawes@{ui} has written
an Amiga version of Rexx, called @{b}ARexx@{ub} (AmigaRexx), now an integral part of
the Amiga operating system.

More  and  more  applications  are  supporting  ARexx,  because  it enables
powerusers  to carry out tasks that would otherwise not have been possible,
or  would  have  taken very long time to complete.  ARexx is also ideal for
making  applications  do specialized, repetitive tasks that would otherwise
have taken much effort to accomplish.

PowerCache  has  a complete ARexx interface.  The syntax and description of
each of these commands can be found in @{"PowerCacheARexx.guide" ALINK "PowerCacheARexx.guide/Main"}.

It  is quite possible that more ARexx commands will be added as PowerCaches
capabilities grow.  If you feel that one or more commands are missing, then
please let me know.
@EndNode

@Node CHelp "What is CHelp"

@{b}CHelp@{ub}  is  a  nifty  little  tool  from  @{i}Robert Wahlström & Mathias Widman@{ui},
designed  for  quickly  finding  structures in the Amiga include files, and
function descriptions in the Amiga @{b}Autodocs@{ub}.

CHelp  was  a  big  help  during  the  development  of PowerCache.  I would
register  it  right  away  (it  is  shareware),  had it not been because it
crashes  quite  often on my machine (too often, actually).  I will probably
end up writing a similar tool myself, that does exactly what I want.
@EndNode

@Node ARexxBox "What is ARexxBox"

@{b}ARexxBox@{ub} is a program that lets you design ARexx interfaces using a graphic
user  interface.   It  is  inspired  by  @{b}GadToolsBox@{ub}  and  behaves somewhat
similar.   After  designing  an  ARexx  interface,  all  you  do  is select
"Generate  Source"  from the main menu, and hey presto!  You have all the C
source code you need to implement that particular ARexx interface.

PowerCache's  ARexx  interface was created largely using ARexxBox, and this
is  probably the main reason why it is as extensive as it is.  Once you get
started  with  ARexxBox, you just can't stop!  Adding a command is so easy,
and  you  don't really think about that until you have to actually code the
commands :-)

ARexxBox  is a wonderful programming aid, and I highly recommend it.  It is
Copyright  by  Michael  Balzer, and can be picked up from Fred Fish, or (if
you have a modem), from the nearest SAN/ADS link.
@EndNode
